## Action Required

- **[Passkey default authentication rollout: review Conditional Access and user communications now](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/13/microsoft-entra-id-security-updates-passkeys-are-the-default-authentication-method-in-entra-id/)** — IMMEDIATE: Passkeys are now the Entra ID default sign-in experience and the SMS/voice authentication model has changed. Audit your Authentication Methods policies, update any Conditional Access policies that reference specific auth method strengths, and prepare end-user communications before users encounter an unexpected prompt change. Organizations with legacy MFA dependencies on SMS/voice need to assess impact now.

- **[Entra Backup and Recovery: assign ownership and build your recovery runbook](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-entra-blog/microsoft-entra-backup-and-recovery-is-now-generally-available/ba-p/4521997)** — ROLLING OUT NOW: Entra Backup and Recovery is live for P1/P2 tenants this week. Before you need it, assign explicit ownership of who can initiate restores, document the recovery procedure for each supported object type, and test a restore in a non-production tenant. Capability without a runbook is not a recovery plan.

- **[Intune Suite licensing in M365 E3/E5: audit add-on spend and update provisioning baselines](https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/t5/microsoft-intune-blog/advanced-microsoft-intune-capabilities-now-available-in/ba-p/4529335)** — EFFECTIVE JULY 1: Advanced Intune Suite capabilities are now included in M365 E5 and select capabilities in M365 E3. Review your current Intune Suite add-on license assignments. Redundant standalone licenses represent unnecessary spend. Update your device configuration baselines to enable newly entitled capabilities such as Endpoint Privilege Management if not already deployed.

- **[ShinyHunters OAuth abuse: audit app consent grants and guest access configurations](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2026/07/13/defending-saas-based-applications-against-shinyhunters-oauth-abuse/)** — ACTIVE THREAT: Microsoft Threat Intelligence has active tracking on ShinyHunters targeting SaaS OAuth flows via vishing and supply-chain compromise. Within the next 30 days, run an OAuth app consent audit in Entra, restrict user consent to verified publishers only, and review external guest access settings for unnecessary permissiveness. This is not a theoretical advisory.